	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Montreal, Quebec GPN Weekend January &#39;04<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 15, 2004</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> GPN Weekend Montreal <br />
King Block, PSQ & Team Tournament (World Cup style)<br />
January 9th – 11th, 2004<br />
<br />
Pre-Tourney Jank<br />
<br />
I figure the best thing for someone that doesn’t write tournament reports anymore is to write a tournament report. It makes the most sense, no? I’ve been re-reading some of my older tournament reports during the holiday season and I was immediately brought back to how much fun I had in Vegas, Spokane, Columbus, Toronto and hell, even Syracuse. So these TRs are become almost like journal entries (notice I didn’t say diary. Those are more for girls and Alan Sagan). So knowing that this weekend in Montreal will be a complete and total blast, how can I not write up a TR to capture this moment in time? My TRs are just your regular Kodak moments J<br />
<br />
So what decks have I prepared for this vast occasion? Friday night is a King Block tournament where a foil ring is up for grabs (I’m still unsure as to whether it being a Mr. Bubbles or Abracadabra). So I’m going for my terribly-unstable deck consisting of straight Rohan with initiative Sauron. I need to get the Some Secret Art of Flame up and running early for my shadow to ever have a hope in hell of either stopping or killing and it almost never happens. Luckily the Archer Troop is pretty scary at 15 strength so hopefully I’ll draw into him early with a Pike or something. I’m missing two Fires Raged Unchecked and the deck is real garbage without those. But I’m playing it anyway. My fellowship is crazy teched against Southrons cuz I want to show Seth from Syracuse how terrible they are. I’m also expecting many people to try Southrons in King Block so hopefully my guess is right. I’m going to get clobbered if I run into a Ringwraith deck, however, so I’ll keep my fingers crossed. And I’m also playing with Theoden just for kicks. I think he is truly terrible but maybe I can get away with playing him in King Block.<br />
<br />
The Friday night even should be fun because Colorado has always been the hotbed for Block play. Matt Olsen tore threw Day Two worlds Towers Block last year and had it not been for all the heavy Block play Colorado plays (their TOC was even Towers Block), he wouldn,t have been able to do it. Syracuse is also considering themselves a bit of a hotbed for Block play so I’m anxious to see these two camps wage war. I’m not especially motivated to win the event myself cuz I’m up to my ears in foil rings (lol).<br />
<br />
As for the two Standard tourneys, I’ll be trying my straight rohan with threat Nazgul (teched against both Rohan and DH). I hope it’ll work out.<br />
<br />
<br />
Thursday, January 8th, 2004<br />
Day Zero<br />
‘…this does not look good for Homestar Runner’<br />
<br />
So getting home from work, I’ve recently unlocked mirror mode in Mario Kart: Double Dash and am dying to try out the Toadette Kart (which Dom thinks is the best kart in the game, he may be right). So a few races later, I’m getting impatient waiting around for Tim to call me from the airport so I head off to Dom’s to get in a playtest game with Malboeuf (it’s his last playtesting session). So I managed to kill half his fellowship (Rohan with Swordthain, Sword, Helms, etc.) at site 5 but he creeps along to site 9 with just merry, eomer and Frodo against like 4 nazgul and still manages to win. Stupid Bounder. So Yako shows up just as Tim calls from the airport. So I drive out in the freezing (-34) weather and pick him, his brother Chris and Will D up. They sound game for going back to Dom’s so we do and play Super Smash Brothers Melee for an hour or so. Dom and I are the clear champions at the end of it (Dom with his cheap-a$$ Marth and me with fast Falco). Props to Chris for using Mr. Game & Watch and Mewtwo just for kicks. Will was easily the worst Kirby player I’ve ever met and Yako (as usual) is surprisingly good at video games (also a Kirby affectionado, those bricks from the heavens are SO annoying). Dom’s gf, Gen, also weighs in with Jigglypuff and keeps putting my Falco to sleep. It’s like listening to Seth talk about Southrons J<br />
<br />
I should also mention that as soon as Chris stepped foot out of my car onto Canadian soil, he immediately hits a patch of ice and his legs fly out from under him landing him squarely on the bum. Too funny…<br />
<br />
So we order some terrible Montreal pizza and Will points out how Canadians put the pepperoni UNDER the cheese (which I find especially stupid as well). Our city has just awful pizza and it’s pretty hard to ever be impressed (especially after you’ve been to New York). We then head out to Hurley’s Irish Pub where Tim and I have a couple pints of cider and Guinness while Chris and Will order up some Long Island Iced Teas and White Russians. Tim and I were getting the drinks cuz we figured the boys would get carded so while Tim and I are ordering these girlie drinks, these chicks at the bar are laughing at us at the bartender , Mark, puts two white Russians right in our faces. We kept telling them they weren’t for us but it was useless. How embarrassing. How can those guys order drinks like that?<br />
<br />
We then head on out to the Ruby Foo’s hotel to set up the boys and Will is shocked to discover that he can’t hook up his GameCube to his hotel television (duh). I point the boys towards the closest subway station and burger joint and then it’s midnight and I gotta work the next day, so I go on my merry way. Upon reaching the front desk, I remember that my buddy, Geoff Smith, should have checked in by now so I ring him up and he’s still awake so we get together for a chit chat (he hooks me up with some wicked coffee he brought from Illinois for me to try, and points out how he’s been spotting the Tim Horton’s around town. Too cool.). We catch up and he tells me he’s got engaged and all sort of wonderful news like that. So I’m getting tired so I jet home, race a few more Kart races and get to bed.<br />
<br />
<br />
Friday, January 09, 2004<br />
Day One<br />
‘…before I drink a tall glass of melonade, I like to eat about 147 fluffy-puff marshmallows. Seriously guys, they’re the best.’<br />
<br />
So I have to go to work today L  but I recently acquired some MacDonald’s coupons so I hit up breakfast with a 2-for-1 on Sausage McMuffins. Yum. Next on the list (after a morning of posting on the Decktech and GPN message boards, is meeting up with my buddy Matt Mitchell for some last minute playtesting over the lunch hour (or is it three hours with the boss away?).  <br />
<br />
I show up and Steve Judge is there as a surprise so I start up a game of King Block with Matt. Half way thru the game, Geoff, Tim, Will and Chris show up so Geoff gets in a game of King (I think) with Steve while I run to nine against Matt’s southrons (my tech worked like a charm. Although two Red Wraths on Gandalf was an unexpected surprise).<br />
<br />
So the 7 of us go on off to the Old Dublin Pub for awesome burgers and booze. Will, Chris and I all order Smirnoff Ice which, apparently, is much more alcoholic in Canada than in the states. So we get kinda buzzed and I head back into work all light-headed. <br />
<br />
I get greeted by the really cute girl at work who tells me I’m beautiful and how profound her love for me is. I’m thinking the Smirnoff Ice is making me a little bit loopy but it’s actually happening. So I turn bright red and smile back and head over to my desk wondering what the hell I do now…. <br />
<br />
Nothing I guess (she’s married, crap). So I surf some more GPN and Decktech and wait around for Kirk England to call me cuz he’s supposed to be picking me up. At 3pm he’s at his hotel but the second car from Syracuse is an hour late. They don’t know where Steve is and I can’t decide if he’s lost or if the border patrol decided to check his prostate. <br />
<br />
So he calls me up like at 4pm and has missed the downtown exit so I spend the next 20 minutes with him on the phone trying to guide him to my office. He gets here ok and then we go to my house to get the car and drive off to the tournament.<br />
<br />
We arrive and there’s like 24 people or so for the King Block which is very decent. There’s also two pool tables in the tournament room so Malboeuf and Tim, Will and Chris just keeping playing games until the event starts. Prize is a foil Abracadabra so people are pretty into winning.<br />
<br />
Round One.<br />
John ‘Fuzzy’ Ellis! <br />
Rohan – Ringwraith<br />
Good: John rocks and is always looking to improve his play so every game with him always feels like a good learning experience.<br />
Bad: The game was painfully slow but that’s okay and understandable. <br />
Ugly: John plays two corrupts to overwhelm some of my companions which was a nasty surprise. John forgets to use his Out of Sight & Shot at site nine to win the game.<br />
Result: FW site 9. whew that was close…<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Matt ‘Treeplanter’ Brochu!<br />
Gondor-Gandalf<br />
Good: Brochu rocks at this game so I’m going to be very challenged for a win<br />
Bad: I couldn’t pull off my traditional anti-brochu swarm at site 4<br />
Ugly: 6 or 7 sauron minions at site 9 after his double move with 5 companions<br />
Results: FW shadow kill site 9. Best part is that Brochu ripped my deck to pieces on GPN calling it a ‘kid’s’ deck. And it schooled him J<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Josh Cornwall-Mott<br />
Weenie swarm – Rohan<br />
Good: Josh is fun when he’s relaxed<br />
Bad: I doubled to 5 with 3 minions already on the table<br />
Ugly: 5 more minions come out with only 6 companions on the table<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 5. I really should not have doubled. My shadow was setting up nicely<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Simon F.<br />
Sauron threat swarm – Rohan<br />
Good: Simon was a crazy fun opponent<br />
Bad: 5 orcs on 4 companions site 5 and me with no hobbit sword<br />
Ugly: site 2 he players a host of udon and kills my eomer. Then he moves to 2 and my mordor warrior kills HIS Eomer. That was funny<br />
Result: FL shadow kill site 5<br />
<br />
Round Five<br />
Matt Mitchell!<br />
Rohan – Southrons<br />
Good: Matt and I both have foil abracadabras so this was a cool match up<br />
Bad: 2 Mustering for Battle in my mulligan hand. Terrible.<br />
Ugly: I had the worst shadow draws ever this game. I had teched against his shadow but couldn’t stop his fellowship ever. Since when does Matt double move all the time?!<br />
Result: FL site 9, my first tournament loss to Matt. Wicked.<br />
<br />
So I go 2-3 and come no where close to winning another foil ring. I decide that Rohan is garbage against Nazgul and Sauron swarm in King Block and my Sauron Initiative isn’t too bad but you really need 3 or 4 Fires Raged Unchecked (which I didn,t have). So I decide Seth’s deck is total garbage and I tear it to pieces that night.<br />
<br />
So Martin Paquette (I think that’s his name) wins the foil ring (even tho Dom says that Patrick Malboeuf won it) with this amazing Sauron-threat Orc Officer deck. He corrupted Pat Malbeouf in the finals who was playing Dom’s ‘unbeatable’ king block deck. So the prize support is legendary for such a small tournament and I announce that we’re going to Hurley’s Irish Pub and then the Casino.<br />
<br />
A surprising amount of people actually show up (including the Toronto and Syracuse crews). I find a table upstairs and we have a few pints. Upon arrival, Tim and I step into the music room where Solstice is playing (my buddy, Jonathan Moorman is ripping a wicked-ass fiddle tune he wrote for his gf called New Zealand Reel). Tim is amazed at how awesome the music is but there’s no where to sit so I take a mental note to come back tomorrow night. <br />
<br />
Finally, people start widdling away and then we have a decent size group to take a run to the Montreal Casino. So off we go and there is VERY few people out that night so we get into the underground parking (thanks be to God since it was gosh darnit cold outside). Geoff, Tim and myself find a spot at a 15$ BlackJack table while Josh, Chris, Will and the othershimmer the bar.<br />
<br />
The rest goes like this: Tim’s first 6 hands are all garbage so before he blinks twice, he’s lost almost a hundred bucks and is out. I threw 250 on the table and have lost almost 150 right away as well. Meanwhile, Geoff is up like 60 bucks or so. Anyway a hour or two later, I’m only down 50 bucks and decide to stop there while Geoff stops once he’s broken even. Chris Williams is the only winner of the night with 60 bucks or so. <br />
<br />
It’s not like 3 in the morning so I drive the Colorado boys (and Geoff) back to their hotel and call it quits for the night. <br />
<br />
<br />
Saturday, January 10th, 2004<br />
Day Two<br />
‘Double-fisting’<br />
<br />
So I’m up like at 9 or so and get off to the MacDonald’s for a couple Sausage MacMuffins and a coffee. I arrive early to the PSQ and get set up. 38 people show up for this one which is pretty sweet considering that almost none of them are locals. WTF?<br />
<br />
Dan Jones from Syracuse and I get into the whole handshake thing again and I learn a new one, the Baked Potato(e). Not too bad. Especially when there’s the double baked potato. Josh C-M gets wind of the handshakes and he starts trying them out. He quickly masters the Stale Fish one and has a hoot with it. <br />
<br />
Tim is judging the event along with Josh C-M. Chris and Will are playing this time around. Chris Williams is playing a heavy discard deck which I find hilarious since it causes such a strong NPE sometimes for players that can’t cope. I’m insanely jealous that I didn’t think of playing that type of deck as well. Darn.<br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Will Dineaga<br />
Gondor-Elf / Naz Threats<br />
Good: Will totally rocks and is probably looking for revenge from the Worlds when I beat him after his brother beat me. This game was all about the good double moves.<br />
Bad: Will should have done a Witch-King – Held Ground thing on me at a really crucial point but elected to try another tactic that was less effective.<br />
Ugly: I get Will to double to 8 and then play 3 Nazgul along with Bill Ferny. Will sends me ELEVEN archery from his fellowship which wipes out each and every minion. I couldn’t believe it. <br />
Result: That of course forces me to double to 9 and I get a FW. <br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Philippe Daoust<br />
Ents / old-school naz<br />
Good: Phil is a great guy who reminds me of like 5 different friends of mine so it’s really cool to see him. <br />
Bad: Enquea twice against him so I managed to kill his two unbound hobbits with Treebeard out with Enraged and Ent Moot. <br />
Ugly: I used ferny to kill pippin early in the game.<br />
Result: Full win at site 9. This match-up was crazy unfavourable for Philippe.<br />
<br />
Funny story here. Philippe is the guy (I think) where I had that controversial game at the last PSQ in Montreal regarding the one twilight token that went mysteriously missing. I ended up getting a warning from Decipher over the stupid thing. Anyway as I’m cleaning up the twilight tokens, one of them goes up my sleeve and I’m like ‘What the heck is in my sleeve (cuz it was cold)’ so I shake out a twilight token and it looks like I was hiding one up my sleeve which is hilarious given the history of my match-up with this guy. Anyway, funny story I thought…<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Martin Prudhomme<br />
Nazgul-Threat / Gondor-elf<br />
Good: Great fast opponent. I love fast play. It’s the easiest way to reduce stress from a game cuz timed wins suck so hard<br />
Bad: This jacka$$ plays FOUR terrible and Evils on my Nazgul. He takes out Cantea and Enquea at KEY MOMENTS where I would have totally ‘clobbered’ his fellowship. <br />
Ugly: I need to trick him into doubling to 9 and he does. With the new site nine, Nazgul kills are finally possible at the end of the game. So I play Witch-King (Pale Blade), Attea, Nelya, Cantea (Fell Beast) against his 4 messed up companions. <br />
Result: FW shadow kill at site 9. He didn’t really have a choice but to double move since I was going to single into nine.<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Michel Alain<br />
Twlight Witch-King (à la BadBeef) – Rohan<br />
Good: This was a great game. I never realized how tough that shadow can be on my Frodo with the scrub ring<br />
Bad: I discard Sam very early thinking I won’t need him this game<br />
Ugly: The very next site after I discarded Sam, I’m up to seven burdens all of a sudden<br />
Result: Full win site 9. <br />
<br />
Round Five<br />
Patrick Malboeuf gosh darnit…<br />
Threat Naz (Gollum) – Merry Rohan<br />
Good: Fun game full of smiles as usual<br />
Bad: I lose Eowyn at site 3 cuz of a necessary double move<br />
Ugly: I couldn’t get near his Eomer. He was so huge.<br />
Result: FL site 9<br />
<br />
Round Six<br />
Justin Desai BOSTON<br />
DH – Naz Threat<br />
I finally get a shot at DH which I’ve teched against<br />
Good: This was the coolest cat I played all day. Crazy laid-back game.<br />
Bad: He stops at 2. <br />
Ugly: Kirk’s beard is getting hard to look at<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
<br />
So not too shabby going 5-1. Malboeuf also went 5-1 after getting corrupted once again but this time by a 15-year old (I think) that was playing with a broken Watcher-in-the-Water/Gollum deck. Patrick didn,t call him on the rules error and he lost. Oh well. I end up in 3rd or 4th place and a foil Morgul Gates for me trouble. WOW. Also a foil Balrog (YUCK). Up for grabs also was a foil Gondor Bowmen, foil Wizard is never late, foil Servant, foil Blade of Gondor, foil Pale Blade, foil Twilight Witch King and Nelya. All in all, best prize support I’ve ever seen in a non-DGMA run event. Truly worth the sortie.<br />
<br />
So afterwards, I gather the troops once again and get everyone to meet up a Brutopia Brew Pub on Crescent street. Some Rams vs South Carolina football game is going on so half the yanks pile into the back room (with the TV) while the rest stay in the side room. Shooters are passed around and before we know it, everyone is a little buzzed (especially Chris Williams who is almost passing out already). <br />
<br />
Now we’re getting hungry towards 8pm, so 16 of us head on over a few blocks (it is SO cold outside) to the Bar-B Barn on Guy Street. I made a reservation and the table is ready so we all sit down and then the waiter, Kenny, tells us we have to all go on ONE bill. That kinda sets me off since it’s completely ridiculous to impose that kind of thing so I make a nice little Theoden-like speech and I talk him down to 2 bills. I’m still really pissed off but it’s the best we can do. <br />
<br />
So everyone orders up ribs pretty much (including Tim who HATES ribs, supposedly). Josh P from Syracuse is the only brave soul to order up a Whole Hawg (9 huge ribs). I ordered 3 with a chicken breast and thought it wouldn’t be enough at first but I ended up barely finishing it. I don’t know how Josh pulled it off. Will Dineaga scored on everyone’s Spanish rice. People were putting business cards up on the walls so I shot mine down to Steve Jones and it lands squarely in Josh’s Spanish r-r-r-r-rice! (which Steve calls out). Lots of laughs throughout the evening and we took a ton of great pictures (including one of our lame waiter). <br />
<br />
One of the best moments was looking over at Dan Jones and he’s in the middle of double-fisting ribs and a chicken wing down his throat. I almost choked to death laughing so hard.  The food was gosh darnit good and we worked out the bills as best we could but everyone doesn’t calculate tax and tip in the same way so the two bill payers (Alex K from Toronto and what’s his face…) end up getting a little bit screwed. But this is what happens when restaurants have LAME policies regarding big groups. Last time I ever go there with more than 9 people. <br />
<br />
Afterwards the group is mixed in what they want to do. We’re discussing Casino but want to drink a bit more. However, MOST of the group (13 of the 16 men) want to try out Montreal ‘rippers. So off they go to Club Super Sexe while Geoff Smith, Tim McKnight and I head back to Hurley’s Irish Pub to catch some wicked-a$$ irish music and pints.<br />
<br />
We get the table RIGHT in front of the band and are blasted by song after song, set after set of really awesome music. At one point, they sing some song about West Virginia (County Road, take me home…) and I see that Geoff knows all the words and I’ve never heard the song in my life so after the song, I say, ‘that’s enough of that Yankee sh*t, and for half a second, Tim thinks that the Band said that. Pretty funny. <br />
<br />
The 13 other guys were supposed to call us an hour after they left but don’t call us for almost 3 hours in the end. By then, we’re way too tired for Casino so we call it a night and I pack the boys into my car. I should mention that everytime we’ve been driving anywhere, in my little green Honda civic 2-door, we have myself, Will, Chris, the other Chris, Tim and then big Geoff as well. Will is on someone’s lap the whole time screaming about butterscotch so the car rides were really wild. <br />
<br />
We hit up Harvey’s hamburgers at 2 in the morning or so and I introduce the guys to REALLY good fast food burgers. I come T-H-I-S close to throwing up but I stave it off. <br />
<br />
Bring the boys back to the hotel, drive home and collapse in bed, exhausted. <br />
<br />
<br />
Sunday, January 11th, 2004<br />
Day Three<br />
‘…You’re gonna make a fortune…’<br />
<br />
This morning, I wake up a little earlier cuz I promised Geoff Smith a game of cards (since I know I won’t be in the mood for it later on). So I arrive early and get into his room which is FREEZING and he’s all like ‘I don’t know why my room is so cool. The fan must be busted.’ I then walk over to his window and CLOSE it. Good thing I’m a rocket scientist so I can figure this kind of stuff out J<br />
<br />
So Geoff and I get to have our first game of off-line LOTR ever. He starts, plays Elrond and Galadriel and moves to site 2 with Arwen, Fair Elf Maiden and Legolas. I drop WitchKing, Nazgul Sword, Fell Beast and kill Arwen and Legolas. I try to say Good Game but can’t get it out without bursting in laughter. At the next site, Geoff scoops his cards, laughing the whole time and we head over to the event after our really intense one-site game.<br />
<br />
Of course in all my other TRs, I never shut up about Tim Horton’s and there’s one on the way (Geoff is big coffee lover) so introduce him to Canada’s most addictive oily coffee there is. We grab two larges and arrive at the event in plenty of time. <br />
<br />
Matt Mitchell and Dani Picard arrive and have brought me Tim Horton’s coffee as well so I guzzle the first one and start on the second one (I’m going to be shaking something fierce in no time).<br />
<br />
Malboeufs are late as usual so I panick for a little while wondering where my world cup team is. I sit with Tim and see him finishing up his Dunland shadow. He says if our two teams get matched up, him and I should play together and I agreed. <br />
<br />
Pat and Dave Malbeouf finally arrive as do 36 other people so we’re 13 teams of 3 and ready to start a mini-world cup. <br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Us against the team consisting of Josh Cornwall Mott, Tim McKnight and somebody else. We win the coin toss and get to pick pairings. Not too seconds after telling Tim that I would pair myself up against him, I change my mind and pair up against Josh.  Too funny. I didn’t want to touch that Dunland deck with a 10-foot pole.<br />
<br />
So here’s how my game went down:<br />
Josh Cornwall Mott<br />
Naz Threat – DH<br />
Good: I played really really well. Only making one basic mistake of healing the wrong companion at site 6. No biggie.<br />
Bad: This was an alarmingly stressful game. I’d say even more stressful that the Semi-final match between Josh and I at Origins. <br />
Ugly: I’m not a big fan of Josh’s play style which usually induces hatred of him by site 5. At one point, Eowyn is blocking Cantea and Ferny and she is winning the skirmish so Josh calls out ‘JUDGE!’ and asks Will if Eowyn wins her skirmish, do both the other minions take a wound? WTF?! What is this LOTR 101? My gf who’s never played the game once wouldn’t have even asked that question. <br />
After a double move, Josh asks me if I want to move or stay? I answer that I’ll choose not to triple move and stay at the site 6 sanctuary. Weird stuff like that was going on all game. Anyway no big deal, cuz he’s a mega cool guy outside of the game and I look forward to splitting a room with him in Vegas.<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
Both my other teammates won their matches as well, so we advance to round two…<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Team Quebec City (Hahn, Brochu and some other guy)<br />
We lose the coin toss and I end up against Hahn and Pat Malboeuf ends up against Brochu. I have a 2-0 record against Hahn so far so I wasn’t very worried.<br />
<br />
Hahn<br />
BadBeef Shadow (Twilight Witch-King, etc) / Elf-Gondor<br />
Good: This was a great match up and her shadow was much tougher than I anticipated.<br />
Bad: I was missing one card to kill her at 7. I had killed almost 8 companions or so and she pulls out Boromir, Son of Denethor. I play two Nazgul but one of them isn’t fierce so I can’t overwhelm Frodo. <br />
Ugly: I move into site 9 with 8 companions but an exhausted ring-bearer with 8 burdens. She plays Nazgul, Brute, Brute and that’s game. For the second Brute, I refuse to become corrupted and decide to wound my ring-bearer instead to avoid embarrassment. <br />
Result: FL site 9 shadow kill<br />
Both my teammates lose their games with Malboeuf getting corrupted for a third time this weekend.<br />
<br />
Round Three (more French guys)<br />
I had to play Martin<br />
Dunland / Rohan<br />
Martin is the guy that won the King block deck and I always manage to lose to this guy even though he always make 100 mistakes each game<br />
Good: Fun opponent. Martin is always getting better and better and makes fewer and fewer mistakes<br />
Bad: This was as bad a match-up as I could have had<br />
Ugly: I made SO many mistakes this game as did he. Wicked Master really saved the day for me in the end by extending my life way longer than it should have gone on for. <br />
Result: Full Loss shadow kill site 7<br />
Both Malboeufs win their games and we move on (I think)<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Team Quantum!!!<br />
We all cheer in you as we get matched up against our old friends. Team Quantum consisted of John Bernatchez, Peter Wilson and heavyweight Mark Koji. <br />
We lose the coin toss and Koji is all about taking on the number one ranked player in the world, Pat Malboeuf. I take on Bernatchez (I think I’ve never lost to him) and we put Dave Malboeuf against Peter. The beginning of the match is hilarious cuz we don’t see anyway that Dave and I can lose our match-ups. Peter is just sitting there smiling the whole time cuz he’s so happy about the match-up of our two teams. He’s smiling so much that it’s starting to freak out Dave and I have to get Dave to let it go and try to concentrate on his game. It was pretty funny.<br />
<br />
John Bernatchez<br />
Deck: Paul Glickman’s deck of death. Eomer Skilled Tactitian, Dunland<br />
Good: I get the God draw against Dunland. I draw into Greenleaf and Arrow Slits at site one. Giving me a very stupid risky double move to three. I shouldn’t have double moved but it was too tempting cuz I was scared about his fellowship that would continuously get possessions and pumps back from discard pile<br />
Bad: I doubled to 3 against dunland after John plays only a Hides at site 2 (and forgets to draw a card)<br />
Ugly: I get him to double move to three and drop two Nazgul both with fell beasts. Eomer and Eowyn both die  (lol)<br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 4<br />
David Malboeuf manages to beat out Peter Wilson with a Moria swarm but Patrick Malboeuf (rating 2210) manages to get himself corrupted yet again by Mark Koji (1640). There’s also like a 10-yr difference in age. I was SO happy for Mark. I think it’s hilarious.<br />
<br />
Round Five (more French guys)<br />
<br />
This time there are three French guys and we lose the coin flip. One of the guys has been a trouble-maker during the three days of gaming. He’s accused Yako of cheating and pulled a few other undesirable moves. More than anything, since this is the Malboeufs last game ever (or at least for a very long time), I want this guy to be matched up against Dave Malboeuf cuz I know he’ll lose his temper and knock this guy’s clock out. But alas, we lose the coin flip and one of the nice guys picks Dave. I really don’t want to play the jerk so I pick Maximillian Bouchard (who’s the really nice and fun guy) and Pat Malboeuf plays his last game of LOTR against the only a$$ of the entire weekend (not bad considering there were like 50 different players present).<br />
<br />
Max Bouchard<br />
Dunland – Elf-gondor<br />
Good: This guy was a really great guy cuz the Pat Malboeuf game was getting stressful a bit but Max and I kept our cool and kept laughing. I was getting really sarcastic against Pat’s opponent cuz he wouldn’t stop talking and stalling and then I would say how happy I was that Max wasn’t like that. And then he would snap back, ‘the name isn’t Max, it’s Maximillian’ (I was all taken aback but he was just kidding. He had the same kind of humour as me and I didn’t see it coming).<br />
Bad: Why, oh, why did I match myself up against Dunland non-stop today?!<br />
Ugly: I discarded my only Toldea after he decides to add 2 burdens to go to four. DANG. <br />
Result: Full loss site 9. Nazgul just can’t win at site 9 when you single into it.<br />
Dave wins his game and Pat’s game ends up taking forever.<br />
<br />
Pat’s opponent was playing crazy slow and Patrick was trying to speed him up near the end so the game wouldn’t go to time. They end up making a deal that even when time is called (which was two minutes away), they would finish the game and whoever loses concedes. Both players agree. So then what happens is that the guy realizes that if he double moves, his entire fellowship would die but Frodo would probably survive and he would get the timed win so he starts to CHANGE his mind about the deal he just made. At this point, Dave’s face turns red (this happens occasionally) and he asks the guy (roughly translated), ‘Hey what are you doing? Are you trying to buy a punch in the face?’  LOL. Too crazy. So Patrick attempt to concede cuz the guy is being such a jerk but the guy refuses. So they play it out and Pat wins. So ends Pat’s last game of LOTR.<br />
<br />
So now Dom’s team wins the whole thing including a huge amount of cash and 3 uncut rare tengwar sheets. NICE prize support, Tim. Our team wins 3 rare foils (Ugluk’s sword, HIDAN and something terrible) and 18 boosters. The boosters had nothing so we put the rares and stuff on the table and back off. At this point, a flock of players attack the table like seagulls and Dave starts making seagull-like noises (CAW!CAW!) and in about 6 seconds, the players clear and there’s no cards left on the table. It was SO funny.<br />
<br />
So once again I get 16 players together and we drive out to Three Amigos Mexican restaurant where you can get 50 cent tacos on Sundays. We all get great parking spots and Martin Paquettes decides to parallel park his car full speed backwards into another car making this huge CRACK noise. Yako gets out of the car and runs full speed towards the restaurant while I’m yelling out, ‘Flee the scene! Flee the scene!’ I should also mention that Yako has torn up jeans and it’s like 40 below that day. What an idiot J<br />
<br />
So we all sit down but there’s no room for Pat Malboeuf and me at the main table so we get our own romantic table with candles which is shoved under a stairwell. Everytime Pat got up, he would smash his head on the stairs. After the third time of everyone cracking up, Pat would do it on purpose to make the waiter feel bad (cuz we had to get up to get out food since our table was cut off by the group). <br />
<br />
The tacos were the worst I’ve ever had and I wasn’t really embarrassed about bringing everyone to such a terrible restaurant. But we laughed the whole time (as per usual) so it was totally worth it.<br />
<br />
Afterwards we head over to Brutopia once again where I teach everyone the best bar game ever, Tabletop Shuffleboard. Soon teams are created and as usual the Malboeufs are naturals at getting 4-point hangers and all the hard stuff to do. Tim and I form a team and his younger brother, Chris Williams, is quite the natural. So Chris and I on one side with Tim and Will on the other. An epic confrontation, to be sure, and we play a best-of-three series where Tim and I go undefeated. We are interrupted non-stop by good looking girls since we’re right beside the ladies’ bathroom. One girl even comes up to me and wants to learn to play. I start explaining the rules and then she bends over to take a shot and I’m all distracted by the nice a$$ so I stop in mid-phrase and forget what I was talking about. She doesn’t notice but all the guys do and we all have a good laugh. <br />
<br />
Afterwards, there’s nothing to do but hit up the Casino one last time so that’s what we do and it was good. We start by hitting the Royal Ascot which is this Sega-designed horse race game that 50 people can play at once. Tim, Chris, Chris and Will all get terminals beside each other and I’m off at the other end of the track betting all by my lonesome. The next 15-minutes are hilarious cuz Chris Williams is screaming at the horses to run faster and he keeps calling out his number. It was too funny. Meanwhile Will is calling out to his fictional horse, Butterscotch to win the race (yet, there was no entrant named Butterscotch throughout the evening). After losing 10 bucks each, Tim and I say that’s enough and try slots for all of 10 seconds. Chris gets 20 bucks and we move onto BlackJack where I actually nail a 10-dollar table where all five of us can sit down. <br />
<br />
There is a handicap-picture on a chip and the dealer, Paul, tells me that if a handicapped person wants to play, we have to give up the spot. So I’m flying a few sheets to the wind, so I start mouthing off about cripples and war-amps and stuff and then when I sit down, I see the next table over has a player wearing a suit in a wheelchair (I felt so stupid). <br />
<br />
So the five of us manage to play for a bit but Tim has taken 3rd base which I hate cuz everyone can screw with your cards there. Dealer has 10 showing and all of us have 13, 14 or 15. I hit a card and bust and then everyone else passes and stays much to the disdain of Tim who can’t believe that nobody took a card. So anyway, Tim does and it ends up all screwy so Tim changes seats besides me. Paul, the dealer, is really big on lecturing Chris Williams about a bunch of stuff and won’t get off his case. So at one point, Chris says fock and the dealer says, ‘my name’s not fock, it’s Paul.’ Everyone finds this hilarious but I find it lame as hell.<br />
<br />
Chris says later on that he came T-H-I-S close to telling Paul to go back to China (this is especially funny since the dealer is clearly South American and not Chinese). <br />
<br />
So slowly the players get picked off one by one and I’m also getting creamed. Tim then decides that we should up our bets so he puts up 15 and I put up 20. He gets two 8’s and the dealer gets a 6. SWEET. So I tell Tim that he has to split his 8’s. He does and gets a 10 and a 3. I then tell him he has to double down on the 11 and he does and pulls a 7. So now he’s got two 18’s on the table against a dealer 6. He also had 45 bucks running on this. He’s starting to turn green and I tell him, ‘It’s ok. You,re gonna make a fortune here’. The dealer then flips over his hidden card and it’s a 5. He then pulls a 10. Twenty-one. YOUCH. So Tim loses everything and Chris is nice enough to repeat what I said earlier in a mocking tone ‘You’re gonna make a fortune!’<br />
<br />
And with that we start to head out but get distracted by the slots. Chris pours like 5 bucks into one and then I put 3 bucks into the same and pull out 20. The other Chris then hits 40 bucks or so on another slot and Chris steals one of the dollars pouring out and runs back to the other slot that took his money and puts that one in. It was hilarious to watch. <br />
<br />
I then get bored and everyone is still playing slots and I have no change. So I open up my wallet and spot a twenty. I put it into a slot machine and lose it. I then do it again. I lose that one too. I then do it again. And again I lose. This all happens in less than a minute. Will then asks me how I’m doing and I say, ‘I think I just lost 60 bucks but I’m not sure’ I open my wallet and flies come out, ‘Yup I just lost 60 dollars for crying out loud!’ <br />
<br />
I was so pissed. I ended up down 150 bucks over the weekend. Both Chris’s were up. Will was down and Tim was WAY DOWN I think. <br />
<br />
So we take off, hit up the Harvey’s again (I get less sick this time), drive the boys back to the hotel and GPN Weekend ends right when the snow starts falling once again (which weather wise, if you’re Canadian, you know that means it’s about to get a lot warmer.). gosh darnit<br />
<br />
It was a fine weekend of gaming and good fun. I really hope Tim decides to throw another GPN event in Montreal sometime (perhaps when it’s warmer and the fine Montreal women are wearing less clothing).<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
·	Tim  McKnight for organizing the best weekend ever and for being a great friend throughout the weekend. Not many guys choose an Irish Pub over a strip joint. We’re few and far between. Congrats also on being named best-looking LOTR player by Dom’s girlfriend.<br />
·	Geoff Smith for being such an amazing buddy. The weekend wouldn’t have been the same without you. Thanks for the coffee and letting me smoke your deck Sunday morning J   Congrats on getting engaged and hope to see you in Syracuse<br />
·	Yako for working out using Jilly’s as the event location. Without you and the bar, this weekend would NEVER have happened. You rock. <br />
·	Pat Malboeuf for being the only reason I’m still playing LOTR. I’m really going to miss you in Vegas. These trips won’t be the same without you. I hate having to raise my hand everytime I make a joke.<br />
·	Dave Malboeuf for making me laugh like crazy over the last 15 months. I’m really going to miss you guys. Let’s be sure and keep in touch.<br />
·	Will and Chris for being the best guys ever. Can’t wait to see you bastards at all the events this year. Glad you guys had such a good time. I can’t believe how lucky Chris is at casinos.<br />
·	Steve Jones for coming up with his crew and hanging out with us, having laughs and all that junk<br />
·	Dan Jones for being so funny, it makes me wish he was MY brother. <br />
·	Kirk for coming up to our fun event and having such a good time, that he immediately started organizing his own event as soon as he got home<br />
·	Seth for developing yet another handshake<br />
·	Josh P for not going to the hospital after eating a whole hawg<br />
·	Josh C-M for coming down and for being such a ‘funny guy’ with those frickin’ annoying handshakes. ‘Ok…seriously.. let’s shake hands J<br />
·	Jake Denley and Steve Sy for coming down from Ottawa for our little weekend of gaming. You guys are the best. And by best, I mean terrible card players (lol)<br />
·	Brochu and hanh for coming down from Quebec City<br />
·	Did I mention props for Geoff Smith yet? If I did, well here’s some more for flying from Illinois<br />
·	Justin and his crew from Boston. That was wicked awesome for you guys to come up<br />
·	Mark Koji for corrupting the best of the best<br />
·	Peter Wilson and John Bernatchez for giving it their best and having a good time doing it. It took guts to show up and try your best against all those players.<br />
·	Steve Judge for making two of the events with a ball and chain J<br />
·	Matt Mitchell for beating me for the first time in sanctioned play<br />
·	Dani Picard for the coffee and all the help she offered throughout the weekend<br />
·	Heather for coming up with Kirk<br />
·	John ‘fuzzy’ ellis for always wanting to improve his game and especially for coming out with us kids J<br />
·	All the other cool cats I met like Max Bouchard, Philippe Daoust and all the others I forgot to call out. You guys are what make these events great.<br />
<br />
Slops<br />
·	Paul the dealer<br />
·	Kenny the waiter<br />
·	Mr. Hyde (josh’s game alter-ego)<br />
·	Alex K for making noise when I’m giving out French instructions for those that don’t speak English. And then making comments like Canada would be better off without Quebec (that’s as stupid as saying that Quebec would be better off without Canada) You’re as bad as them, Alex. Stop saying stuff like that.<br />
·	Canada Customs for charging LOTR players when they’re stupid enough to say they plan on ‘trading’ cards on their visit. WTF?<br />
<br />
That’s it boys and girls. Next GPN Weekend is planned for Syracuse, New York near the end of April. Look out for it….<br />
